European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, Nazi occupation.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the middle of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined together, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political unit, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is a mistake.
It is as if one part of a room could be heated while the other remains cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event elicits an echo throughout Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to take in the new post-communist democracies  which is in Europe's interest , a number of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First of all, Europe must promote the community spirit in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
Denn eine lebendige Gesellschaft kann nicht von oben wiederaufgebaut werden.
Europa muss seinen neuen Demokratien also helfen, organischer Teil eines gemeinsamen kontinentalen Bekenntnisses zur Vertiefung und Stärkung der Zivilgesellschaft zu werden.
Je vielfältiger europäische zivilgesellschaftliche Strukturen werden und je mehr sie miteinander verbunden sind, um so besser werden die neuen Demokratien für die Mitgliedschaft in der EU ausgerüstet und um so stabiler werden sie als Staaten sein.
Um dies zu erreichen, muss Europa die neuen Demokratien dazu ermutigen, diverse Solidaraufgaben selbstverwalteten Institutionen und gemeinnützigen oder öffentlichen Dienstleistungsorganisationen zu übertragen.
Je tiefer die Ebene der Umverteilung ist, um so transparenter und ökonomischer wird es sein; und um so besser wird es jene sozialen Bedürfnisse befriedigen, die die zentralen Behörden nicht erkennen können.
The social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its neglect of European solidarity, which led to the Munich capitulation.
This experience is still a strong call for vigilance.
One must confront the evil as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if only governments act.
For government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make decisions quickly and to implement collective decisions rapidly  reforms that were deemed necessary by the recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of overall European security require interventions outside the EU's borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations in which the UN mandate may not come, although an intervention is in the interest of many people, of all of Europe, indeed of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared for it, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
But further things are still needed on the field of preventive security, but it is also necessary to ensure that this security reflects the values of the expanded civil society in Europe.
Tens of thousands of human lives and a huge amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted already at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was timid.
These failures were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without the American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot remain forever dependent on the United States, especially regarding European problems.
It must be capable of reaching its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of reaching agreement on means and methods for the protection of human rights, not only on its own territory but also in areas that may one day join it.
Such an EU enlargement is only conceivable if it proceeds hand in hand with a determined reform of the EU institutions.
I am confident that the government conference on institutional reform will put forward practical proposals for the advancement of the Union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting endeavor to accelerate and make more transparent EU decision-making.
An issue related to institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the certainty that they will not simply be overruled by the larger ones, while at the same time adequately taking into account the size of each individual state.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would not be directly elected, but would be chosen by the parliaments of the member states from their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU  that is, the current Parliament  would therefore reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber would, with the same number of representatives for each country, increase equality.
These changes will eventually require that the EU possess a clear, understandable constitution  a text that all European children could learn.
A constitution of this sort would need two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties of both European citizens and the states, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships with each other.
Such a fundamental law would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal superstate feared by Eurosceptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to better understand it, to see the significance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, to identify with it.
